Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dgkh1975/moby/commits/ee02257553d80c3bb41e3b0ad44cb4e3324bfd65"},{"sha":"ac449d6b5ad29a5086824729ce54eec6b0cc8545","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"daemon/config: rename the default seccomp profile to "builtin"

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dgkh1975/moby/commits/ac449d6b5ad29a5086824729ce54eec6b0cc8545"},{"sha":"68e96f88ee1598563a66a1f53b8844291423fc88","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon.json and daemon --seccomp-profile not accepting "unconfined"

Commit b237189e6c8a4f97be59f08c63cdcb1f2f4680a8 implemented an option to
set the default seccomp profile in the daemon configuration. When that PR
was reviewed, it was discussed to have the option accept the path to a custom
profile JSON file; https://github.com/moby/moby/pull/26276#issuecomment-253546966

However, in the implementation, the special "unconfined" value was not taken into
account. The "unconfined" value is meant to disable seccomp (more factually:
run with an empty profile).

While it's likely possible to achieve this by creating a file with an an empty
(`{}`) profile, and passing the path to that file, it's inconsistent with the
`--security-opt seccomp=unconfined` option on `docker run` and `docker create`,
which is both confusing, and makes it harder to use (especially on Docker Desktop,
where there's no direct access to the VM's filesystem).

This patch adds the missing check for the special "unconfined" value.

Co-authored-by: Tianon Gravi <admwiggin@gmail.com>
Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dgkh1975/moby/commits/68e96f88ee1598563a66a1f53b8844291423fc88"},{"sha":"f8795ed364586acd93f72e206a409e7e0e27edcc","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"daemon: allow "builtin" as valid value for seccomp profiles

This allows containers to use the embedded default profile if a different
default is set (e.g. "unconfined") in the daemon configuration. Without this
option, users would have to copy the default profile to a file in order to
use the default.

The following symbols were accidentally added. This change removes these symbols.
  * tf.quantize_and_dequantize_v4
  * tf.batch_mat_mul_v3
  * tf.sparse_segment_sum_grad

Each of the three changes that accidentally added a symbol did so by creating a new op, then forgetting to create a Python ApiDef marking the op as HIDDEN. The ops were not intended to be directly exposed under the top-level tf namespace.

There are no GitHub usages of any of these symbols, so removing them is safe.

Change-Id: I7023a02980fc9ab954f866e9644710fb20f262ed","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/58d81aebfc68f09cbee82f8925e8d52c746b24bf"},{"sha":"deef39b559d983bdda7deae9b28a06cee598d335","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Remove accidentally added Python symbols.

The following symbols were accidentally added. This change removes these symbols.
  * tf.quantize_and_dequantize_v4
  * tf.batch_mat_mul_v3
  * tf.sparse_segment_sum_grad

Each of the three changes that accidentally added a symbol did so by creating a new op, then forgetting to create a Python ApiDef marking the op as HIDDEN. The ops were not intended to be directly exposed under the top-level tf namespace.

There are no GitHub usages of any of these symbols, so removing them is safe.

1- For async copy ordering, use the estimated elapsed time instead of the time
   copy done is scheduled. This prevents unnecessarily getting blocked behind
   prefetches that happen to have copy start/done that are spaced apart.
2- For the cross-program prefetch buffer freeing optimization, check how much, as
   a ratio of total execution time, would we actually be able to free the buffer
   and don't do the optimization if the buffer will occupied greater than a
   limit (currently set to 60%).

Change-Id: I70b1e6deca70e3d6a50e447fc21d5c5b1ae821b6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/95c84b1e036acb284e61afb8092c0323ef6767d9"},{"sha":"33fc71072452034b80aba79716ace0dc48ce4431","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Simplify heuristics for promotion to int8x32.

Previously, we would upgrade to int8x32 if doing so did not result in a > 2.5x
increase in the input/filter/output size of the conv.

Now we only consider the input/output sizes.  Sometimes the filter increases by
more than 2.5x and we observe that it's still worthwhile to pad.  Anyway I
think this makes more sense, since the increase in the filter size is really a
function of the input/output increases.

As a result we're able to switch the heuristic to the more intuitive "don't
expand input/output by 2x or more".

Change-Id: I4ef3394ca4fb913f26c8821e8c8fdabb11cc03cb","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vijayphoenix/tensorflow/commits/c92c130b2cce8faad026944634b467376509f991"},{"sha":"56bbd227f69b9a5314b884f8ce128fa745d20c18","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[PJRT] Unroll the inner loops of the memcpy kernel again.

* Add __restrict qualifiers on the transpose plan Node pointers. Since the data pointers are passed via char*, aliasing rules would allow the char* to alias the Node pointers. Adding __restrict allows the compiler to promote members of the plan nodes into registers.
* Unroll the memcpy plan nodes again. We already did this in a previous change, but temporarily reverted it when updating the handling of trailing tiles. These loops can be tight loops around a memcpy(), so it is important that we keep loop overheads low.

Some ops don't follow the common semantics (i.e., empty or anonymous
`shared_name` guaranteeing unique allocated resources) so we can't utilize those
semantics in resource alias analysis. See e.g. `FusedResizeAndPadConvFunctor`.
Also added warning about resource-allocating ops that are treated conservatively
in resource alias analysis.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/moby/commits/ac449d6b5ad29a5086824729ce54eec6b0cc8545"},{"sha":"68e96f88ee1598563a66a1f53b8844291423fc88","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon.json and daemon --seccomp-profile not accepting "unconfined"

Commit b237189e6c8a4f97be59f08c63cdcb1f2f4680a8 implemented an option to
set the default seccomp profile in the daemon configuration. When that PR
was reviewed, it was discussed to have the option accept the path to a custom
profile JSON file; https://github.com/moby/moby/pull/26276#issuecomment-253546966

However, in the implementation, the special "unconfined" value was not taken into
account. The "unconfined" value is meant to disable seccomp (more factually:
run with an empty profile).

While it's likely possible to achieve this by creating a file with an an empty
(`{}`) profile, and passing the path to that file, it's inconsistent with the
`--security-opt seccomp=unconfined` option on `docker run` and `docker create`,
which is both confusing, and makes it harder to use (especially on Docker Desktop,
where there's no direct access to the VM's filesystem).

This patch adds the missing check for the special "unconfined" value.

Co-authored-by: Tianon Gravi <admwiggin@gmail.com>
Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/moby/commits/68e96f88ee1598563a66a1f53b8844291423fc88"},{"sha":"f8795ed364586acd93f72e206a409e7e0e27edcc","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"daemon: allow "builtin" as valid value for seccomp profiles

This allows containers to use the embedded default profile if a different
default is set (e.g. "unconfined") in the daemon configuration. Without this
option, users would have to copy the default profile to a file in order to
use the default.

[{"sha":"99002d4a4336e2c5a9d6fd64e64dda5325af0827","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Fix unchecked int32 indexing in some GPU kernels

- Many op kernels use the To32Bit() function, which does not do any
  bounds checking and can cause silent corruption due to int32
  overflow.
  E.g., tf.zeros/ones/fill silently give incorrect results when the
  number of elements is >= 2**31.
- This commit adds a new helper function MaybeWith32BitIndexing() that
  checks the indexing bounds and converts tensors to 32-bit only if
  it is safe to do so (and only for GPU devices). This fixes the
  cases that were previously broken, and simplifies the ones that
  already had explicit bounds checks.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/99002d4a4336e2c5a9d6fd64e64dda5325af0827"},{"sha":"dba2a5db51ee95efd79c96d18f72d962d7d8bfbd","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Simplify code in MaybeWith32BitIndexingImpl","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/dba2a5db51ee95efd79c96d18f72d962d7d8bfbd"},{"sha":"2cf981016f64a4d185b31958403020f13a730698","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Add workaround for when num_bits=0 in GpuRadixSort

   copy done is scheduled. This prevents unnecessarily getting blocked behind
   prefetches that happen to have copy start/done that are spaced apart.
2- For the cross-program prefetch buffer freeing optimization, check how much, as
   a ratio of total execution time, would we actually be able to free the buffer
   and don't do the optimization if the buffer will occupied greater than a
   limit (currently set to 60%).

Change-Id: I4ef3394ca4fb913f26c8821e8c8fdabb11cc03cb","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kevint324/tensorflow/commits/c92c130b2cce8faad026944634b467376509f991"},{"sha":"56bbd227f69b9a5314b884f8ce128fa745d20c18","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[PJRT] Unroll the inner loops of the memcpy kernel again.

* Add __restrict qualifiers on the transpose plan Node pointers. Since the data pointers are passed via char*, aliasing rules would allow the char* to alias the Node pointers. Adding __restrict allows the compiler to promote members of the plan nodes into registers.
* Unroll the memcpy plan nodes again. We already did this in a previous change, but temporarily reverted it when updating the handling of trailing tiles. These loops can be tight loops around a memcpy(), so it is important that we keep loop overheads low.

[{"sha":"88d121899aca8fec537003360010f077f0880541","author":{"name":"Juan","email":"bfe93a71cb86c31fefdccaf2f35c1c292a434187@fb.com"},"message":"[DevTools] Support extended source maps with named hooks information (#22010)

## Summary

Adds support for statically extracting names for hook calls from source code, and extending source maps with that information so that DevTools does not have to directly parse source code at runtime, which will speed up the Named Hooks feature and allow it to be enabled by default.

Specifically, this PR includes the following parts:

- [x] Adding logic to statically extract relevant hook names from the parsed source code (i.e. the babel ast). Note that this logic differs slightly from the existing logic in that the existing logic also uses runtime information from DevTools (such as whether given hooks are a custom hook) to extract names for hooks, whereas this code is meant to run entirely at build time, so it does not rely on that information.
- [x] Generating an encoded "hook map", which encodes the information about a hooks *original* source location, and it's corresponding name. This "hook map" will be used to generate extended source maps, included tentatively under an extra `x_react_hook_map` field. The map itself is formatted and encoded in a very similar way as how the `names` and `mappings` fields of a standard source map are encoded ( = Base64 VLQ delta coding representing offsets into a string array), and how the "function map" in Metro is encoded, as suggested in #21782. Note that this initial version uses a very basic format, and we are not implementing our own custom encoding, but reusing the `encode` function from `sourcemap-codec`.
- [x] Updating the logic in `parseHookNames` to check if the source maps have been extended with the hook map information, and if so use that information to extract the hook names without loading the original source code. In this PR we are manually generating extended source maps in our tests in order to test that this functionality works as expected, even though we are not actually generating the extended source maps in production.

The second stage of this work, which will likely need to occur outside this repo, is to update bundlers such as Metro to use these new primitives to actually generate source maps that DevTools can use.

### Follow-ups

- Enable named hooks by default when extended source maps are present
- Support looking up hook names when column numbers are not present in source map.
- Measure performance improvement of using extended source maps (manual testing suggests ~4 to 5x faster)
- Update relevant bundlers to generate extended source maps.

## Test Plan

- yarn flow
- Tests still pass
  - yarn test
  - yarn test-build-devtools
- Named hooks still work on manual test of browser extension on a few different apps (code sandbox, create-react-app, facebook).
- For new functionality:
  - New tests for statically extracting hook names.
  - New tests for using extended source maps to look up hook names at runtime.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/undefined-degisn/react/commits/88d121899aca8fec537003360010f077f0880541"},{"sha":"280e3f936f89583b44e10f29ed0ed0155b50ab8a","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTools: Scheduling profiler: Add vertical scroll bar (#22005)

## Summary

Follow up from https://github.com/facebook/react/pull/22010.

As suggested by @motiz88, update the way the react sources metadata is stored within the fb sources metadata. Specifically,  instead of `x_facebook_sources` directly containing a hook map in the second position of the metadata tuple for a given source, it contains the react sources metadata itself, which is also a tuple of react sources metadata for a given source, and which contains the hook map in the first position. This way the react sources metadata tuple can be extended to contain more react-specific metadata without taking up more positions in the top-level facebook sources metadata.

As part of this change:
- Adds more precise Flow types, mostly borrowed from Metro
- Fixes the facebook sources field name (we were using `x_fb_sources` but it should be `x_facebook_sources`

Some ops don't follow the common semantics (i.e., empty or anonymous
`shared_name` guaranteeing unique allocated resources) so we can't utilize those
semantics in resource alias analysis. See e.g. `FusedResizeAndPadConvFunctor`.
Also added warning about resource-allocating ops that are treated conservatively
in resource alias analysis.

The for loop that follows this check assumes that `axis` is between `0` and `input_dims.size`. If user supplied `axis` is negative, the if code before this check is supposed to bring it back to positive (similar to how in Python one can do `l[-3]` to mean `l[-3 + len(l)]`).

  number of elements is >= 2**31.

  cases that were previously broken, and simplifies the ones that

Change-Id: Ib5f5bf3bc358dbdca6b4a39c8db2f4b782d9ed47","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/e2d72a20b241fe2dca1dad1eb391350460c06060"},{"sha":"858825431c21ebdde772e9e9d9b91e11786c2cb6","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Make it possible to return a C++ `ShardedDeviceArray`.

This **will** be a **breaking** change, as pxla.ShardedDeviceArray constructor won't be valid anymore:
- for the next Jax release
- on the condition _USE_EXPERIMENTAL_CPP_SDA is switch to `_xla_extension_version > xx` and with the associated jaxlib release.

I am already adding the impact for the users in the CHANGELOG, we can still move it to the next version depending on when it's shipped.

Similarly to JAX.jit, for which we have a C++ `DeviceArray` and a Python `_DeviceArray`, we will introduce 2 objects for ShardedDeviceArray, with the Python object only for JAX extensions not compatible with the C++ object (e.g. Cloud TPU).

- Add `make_sharded_device_array` to be used within JAX and for hackers that need to construct SDA objects.
- Make sure the C++ object is valid by
  (a) extending `DeviceArrayBase` (done in Python), as it brings a bunch of methods and enable `isinstance(x, DeviceArray)`
  (b) Adding the same methods as the Python SDA.

NOTE: mypy has troubled with the " -> pxla.ShardedDeviceArray` function return type annotation, I had to remove 2.

Change-Id: Iea210a80b375cf4130ee42fe36d1e302c6b129df","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/dfad859f8262dce623af19db3763bdbe439c59dd"},{"sha":"8b5102cf53bc57319764ff6accfa52895f2c0f0a","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Fix a problem in running a TRTEngineOp native segment with int32
values as inputs.

A TRTEngineOp has all its inputs on device memory. On the other hand,
TensorFlow assumes all function arguments with int32 values are on host memory
unless the kIntsOnDeviceAttr attribute is set to true. This change sets up the
kIntsOnDeviceAttr attribute for the TRTEngineOp native segment function to
support the TensorFlow execution of the function.

Modify an existing test to test the situation.

[{"sha":"56bbd227f69b9a5314b884f8ce128fa745d20c18","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[PJRT] Unroll the inner loops of the memcpy kernel again.

* Add __restrict qualifiers on the transpose plan Node pointers. Since the data pointers are passed via char*, aliasing rules would allow the char* to alias the Node pointers. Adding __restrict allows the compiler to promote members of the plan nodes into registers.
* Unroll the memcpy plan nodes again. We already did this in a previous change, but temporarily reverted it when updating the handling of trailing tiles. These loops can be tight loops around a memcpy(), so it is important that we keep loop overheads low.

`shared_name` guaranteeing unique allocated resources) so we can't utilize those

in resource alias analysis.

As TFLite team delivered the Signature concept recently
(https://www.tensorflow.org/lite/guide/signatures), it is a good time to rethink
about the representative_dataset method behavior.

As per the TensorFlow product design and TensorFlow MLIR behaviors, it is
really impossible to keep the input ordering same as before.

Instead of depending on the tensor indices, it would be better to depend on the
input names, specified in the signature table.

For example,

def representative_dataset():
    for _ in range(100):
      image = np.random.rand(1, 244, 244, 3).astype(np.float32)
      bias = np.random.rand(1, 10).astype(np.float32)
      yield {"image": image, "bias": bias}

## Summary

Adds support for statically extracting names for hook calls from source code, and extending source maps with that information so that DevTools does not have to directly parse source code at runtime, which will speed up the Named Hooks feature and allow it to be enabled by default.

Specifically, this PR includes the following parts:

- [x] Adding logic to statically extract relevant hook names from the parsed source code (i.e. the babel ast). Note that this logic differs slightly from the existing logic in that the existing logic also uses runtime information from DevTools (such as whether given hooks are a custom hook) to extract names for hooks, whereas this code is meant to run entirely at build time, so it does not rely on that information.
- [x] Generating an encoded "hook map", which encodes the information about a hooks *original* source location, and it's corresponding name. This "hook map" will be used to generate extended source maps, included tentatively under an extra `x_react_hook_map` field. The map itself is formatted and encoded in a very similar way as how the `names` and `mappings` fields of a standard source map are encoded ( = Base64 VLQ delta coding representing offsets into a string array), and how the "function map" in Metro is encoded, as suggested in #21782. Note that this initial version uses a very basic format, and we are not implementing our own custom encoding, but reusing the `encode` function from `sourcemap-codec`.
- [x] Updating the logic in `parseHookNames` to check if the source maps have been extended with the hook map information, and if so use that information to extract the hook names without loading the original source code. In this PR we are manually generating extended source maps in our tests in order to test that this functionality works as expected, even though we are not actually generating the extended source maps in production.

The second stage of this work, which will likely need to occur outside this repo, is to update bundlers such as Metro to use these new primitives to actually generate source maps that DevTools can use.

### Follow-ups

- Enable named hooks by default when extended source maps are present
- Support looking up hook names when column numbers are not present in source map.
- Measure performance improvement of using extended source maps (manual testing suggests ~4 to 5x faster)
- Update relevant bundlers to generate extended source maps.

## Test Plan

- yarn flow
- Tests still pass
  - yarn test
  - yarn test-build-devtools
- Named hooks still work on manual test of browser extension on a few different apps (code sandbox, create-react-app, facebook).
- For new functionality:
  - New tests for statically extracting hook names.
  - New tests for using extended source maps to look up hook names at runtime.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/colegillespie/react/commits/88d121899aca8fec537003360010f077f0880541"},{"sha":"280e3f936f89583b44e10f29ed0ed0155b50ab8a","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTools: Scheduling profiler: Add vertical scroll bar (#22005)

## Summary

Follow up from https://github.com/facebook/react/pull/22010.

As suggested by @motiz88, update the way the react sources metadata is stored within the fb sources metadata. Specifically,  instead of `x_facebook_sources` directly containing a hook map in the second position of the metadata tuple for a given source, it contains the react sources metadata itself, which is also a tuple of react sources metadata for a given source, and which contains the hook map in the first position. This way the react sources metadata tuple can be extended to contain more react-specific metadata without taking up more positions in the top-level facebook sources metadata.

As part of this change:
- Adds more precise Flow types, mostly borrowed from Metro
- Fixes the facebook sources field name (we were using `x_fb_sources` but it should be `x_facebook_sources`

## Test Plan

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/ac449d6b5ad29a5086824729ce54eec6b0cc8545"},{"sha":"68e96f88ee1598563a66a1f53b8844291423fc88","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon.json and daemon --seccomp-profile not accepting "unconfined"

Commit b237189e6c8a4f97be59f08c63cdcb1f2f4680a8 implemented an option to
set the default seccomp profile in the daemon configuration. When that PR
was reviewed, it was discussed to have the option accept the path to a custom
profile JSON file; https://github.com/moby/moby/pull/26276#issuecomment-253546966

However, in the implementation, the special "unconfined" value was not taken into
account. The "unconfined" value is meant to disable seccomp (more factually:
run with an empty profile).

While it's likely possible to achieve this by creating a file with an an empty
(`{}`) profile, and passing the path to that file, it's inconsistent with the
`--security-opt seccomp=unconfined` option on `docker run` and `docker create`,
which is both confusing, and makes it harder to use (especially on Docker Desktop,
where there's no direct access to the VM's filesystem).

This patch adds the missing check for the special "unconfined" value.

Co-authored-by: Tianon Gravi <admwiggin@gmail.com>
Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/68e96f88ee1598563a66a1f53b8844291423fc88"},{"sha":"f8795ed364586acd93f72e206a409e7e0e27edcc","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"daemon: allow "builtin" as valid value for seccomp profiles

This allows containers to use the embedded default profile if a different
default is set (e.g. "unconfined") in the daemon configuration. Without this
option, users would have to copy the default profile to a file in order to
use the default.

[{"sha":"b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20","author":{"name":"Håkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Add pre-load CPU feature guard check

Compile a small shared library that performs an x86 CPU feature guard
check that compares the features enabled during compile-time with the
features available at run-time (using the `CPUID` instruction). This
comparison is done during static initialization and the process is
aborted with an error message if we have compiled with a feature that is
not supported by the current CPU.

Such a check is already performed during static initialization of the
library `libtensorflow_framework.so.2`, but since this library performs
many actions during initialization, there is a high risk of triggering
an illegal instruction before we reach the check, depending on the
(undefined) static initialization order.

Because of this we compile a separate shared library that we load as a
self-check before loading `_pywrap_tensorflow_internal.so`.

We also change to use `<iostream>` for printing in case of a failed
check, as use of the logging framework might itself trigger an
illegal instruction (it did in my testing).

Tested by attempting to use a wheel built with AVX-512 on an AMD CPU:

Before:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
Illegal instruction
```

After:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
The TensorFlow library was compiled to use AVX512F instructions, but these aren't available on your machine.
Aborted

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/ac449d6b5ad29a5086824729ce54eec6b0cc8545"},{"sha":"68e96f88ee1598563a66a1f53b8844291423fc88","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon.json and daemon --seccomp-profile not accepting "unconfined"

Commit b237189e6c8a4f97be59f08c63cdcb1f2f4680a8 implemented an option to
set the default seccomp profile in the daemon configuration. When that PR
was reviewed, it was discussed to have the option accept the path to a custom
profile JSON file; https://github.com/moby/moby/pull/26276#issuecomment-253546966

However, in the implementation, the special "unconfined" value was not taken into
account. The "unconfined" value is meant to disable seccomp (more factually:
run with an empty profile).

While it's likely possible to achieve this by creating a file with an an empty
(`{}`) profile, and passing the path to that file, it's inconsistent with the
`--security-opt seccomp=unconfined` option on `docker run` and `docker create`,
which is both confusing, and makes it harder to use (especially on Docker Desktop,
where there's no direct access to the VM's filesystem).

This patch adds the missing check for the special "unconfined" value.

Co-authored-by: Tianon Gravi <admwiggin@gmail.com>
Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/68e96f88ee1598563a66a1f53b8844291423fc88"},{"sha":"f8795ed364586acd93f72e206a409e7e0e27edcc","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"daemon: allow "builtin" as valid value for seccomp profiles

This allows containers to use the embedded default profile if a different
default is set (e.g. "unconfined") in the daemon configuration. Without this
option, users would have to copy the default profile to a file in order to
use the default.

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kcak11/react/commits/06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb"},{"sha":"d7dce572c7453737a685e791e7afcbc7e2b2fe16","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove internal `act` builds from public modules (#21721)

I've left the the renderer-specific `act` entry points because legacy
mode tests need to also be wrapped in `batchedUpdates`. Next, I'll update
the tests to use `batchedUpdates` manually when needed.

* Migrates tests to use internal module directly

Instead of the `unstable_concurrentAct` exports. Now we can drop those
from the public builds.

I put it in the jest-react package since that's where we put our other
testing utilities (like `toFlushAndYield`). Not so much so it can be
consumed publicly (nobody uses that package except us), but so it works
with our build tests.

* Remove unused internal fields

These were used by the old act implementation. When migrating some internal tests I found it annoying that I couldn't
return anything from the `act` scope. You would have to declare the
variable on the outside then assign to it. But this doesn't play well
with type systems — when you use the variable, you have to check
the type.

Before:

```js
let renderer;
act(() => {
  renderer = ReactTestRenderer.create(<App />);
})

// Type system can't tell that renderer is never undefined
renderer?.root.findByType(Component);
```

After:

```js
const renderer = await act(() => {
  return ReactTestRenderer.create(<App />);
})
renderer.root.findByType(Component);
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kcak11/react/commits/cae635054e17a6f107a39d328649137b83f25972"},{"sha":"d483463bc86555decb3e8caa18459d1d0f7c0148","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Updated scripts and config to replace "master" with "main" branch (#21768)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kcak11/react/commits/d483463bc86555decb3e8caa18459d1d0f7c0148"},{"sha":"83f38d07689b8b750b7d96e17647a8978b836154","author":{"name":"dependabot[bot]","email":"1c358da00a777d4e9898c1280ab801e2df165188@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Bump ecstatic from 2.2.1 to 2.2.2 in /scripts/bench (#20468)

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Legalize mhlo.not to TFLogicalNotOp

In fact, there was a pattern in dealing with mhlo.not. However, that operation included a mistake. It required the operand to be TF_IntOrFpTensor and it also demanded SameOperandsAndResultType. Under this circumstance, the pattern became a vacuous one as the result type of NotOp must be Bool and the input operand is IntOrFp. I fixed this bug by simply replacing TF_IntOrFpTensor with TF_BoolTensor in the definition of the pattern.

The mesh hash contains the vips which now ensures that the watchdog
will regenerate the xds config when needed.

This enables us to remove this extra outbounds in the dataplane resource
and simply generate the outbounds and the dns config in the dataplane_proxy_builder

Users upgrading to this version using transparent proxy in universal will need to reapply all the dps to get rid of the `outbounds` generated previously.

## Summary

Adds support for statically extracting names for hook calls from source code, and extending source maps with that information so that DevTools does not have to directly parse source code at runtime, which will speed up the Named Hooks feature and allow it to be enabled by default.

Specifically, this PR includes the following parts:

- [x] Adding logic to statically extract relevant hook names from the parsed source code (i.e. the babel ast). Note that this logic differs slightly from the existing logic in that the existing logic also uses runtime information from DevTools (such as whether given hooks are a custom hook) to extract names for hooks, whereas this code is meant to run entirely at build time, so it does not rely on that information.
- [x] Generating an encoded "hook map", which encodes the information about a hooks *original* source location, and it's corresponding name. This "hook map" will be used to generate extended source maps, included tentatively under an extra `x_react_hook_map` field. The map itself is formatted and encoded in a very similar way as how the `names` and `mappings` fields of a standard source map are encoded ( = Base64 VLQ delta coding representing offsets into a string array), and how the "function map" in Metro is encoded, as suggested in #21782. Note that this initial version uses a very basic format, and we are not implementing our own custom encoding, but reusing the `encode` function from `sourcemap-codec`.
- [x] Updating the logic in `parseHookNames` to check if the source maps have been extended with the hook map information, and if so use that information to extract the hook names without loading the original source code. In this PR we are manually generating extended source maps in our tests in order to test that this functionality works as expected, even though we are not actually generating the extended source maps in production.

The second stage of this work, which will likely need to occur outside this repo, is to update bundlers such as Metro to use these new primitives to actually generate source maps that DevTools can use.

### Follow-ups

- Enable named hooks by default when extended source maps are present
- Support looking up hook names when column numbers are not present in source map.
- Measure performance improvement of using extended source maps (manual testing suggests ~4 to 5x faster)
- Update relevant bundlers to generate extended source maps.

## Test Plan

- yarn flow
- Tests still pass
  - yarn test
  - yarn test-build-devtools
- Named hooks still work on manual test of browser extension on a few different apps (code sandbox, create-react-app, facebook).
- For new functionality:
  - New tests for statically extracting hook names.
  - New tests for using extended source maps to look up hook names at runtime.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/taneliang/react/commits/88d121899aca8fec537003360010f077f0880541"},{"sha":"280e3f936f89583b44e10f29ed0ed0155b50ab8a","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTools: Scheduling profiler: Add vertical scroll bar (#22005)

## Summary

Follow up from https://github.com/facebook/react/pull/22010.

As suggested by @motiz88, update the way the react sources metadata is stored within the fb sources metadata. Specifically,  instead of `x_facebook_sources` directly containing a hook map in the second position of the metadata tuple for a given source, it contains the react sources metadata itself, which is also a tuple of react sources metadata for a given source, and which contains the hook map in the first position. This way the react sources metadata tuple can be extended to contain more react-specific metadata without taking up more positions in the top-level facebook sources metadata.

As part of this change:
- Adds more precise Flow types, mostly borrowed from Metro
- Fixes the facebook sources field name (we were using `x_fb_sources` but it should be `x_facebook_sources`

## Test Plan

Improves transposes such as f32[1, 1024, 1]{2, 1, 0} -> f32[1, 1024, 1]{1, 2, 0}T(2, 128). The loop simplification cannot remove the degenerate second-minor `1` dimension and it was ending up innermost. But there's no reason why we can't treat the 1024 dimension as innermost in the input, and then this becomes a decently-sized memcpy() kernel.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Legalize mhlo.not to TFLogicalNotOp

In fact, there was a pattern in dealing with mhlo.not. However, that operation included a mistake. It required the operand to be TF_IntOrFpTensor and it also demanded SameOperandsAndResultType. Under this circumstance, the pattern became a vacuous one as the result type of NotOp must be Bool and the input operand is IntOrFp. I fixed this bug by simply replacing TF_IntOrFpTensor with TF_BoolTensor in the definition of the pattern.

As TFLite team delivered the Signature concept recently
(https://www.tensorflow.org/lite/guide/signatures), it is a good time to rethink
about the representative_dataset method behavior.

As per the TensorFlow product design and TensorFlow MLIR behaviors, it is
really impossible to keep the input ordering same as before.

Instead of depending on the tensor indices, it would be better to depend on the
input names, specified in the signature table.

For example,

def representative_dataset():
    for _ in range(100):
      image = np.random.rand(1, 244, 244, 3).astype(np.float32)
      bias = np.random.rand(1, 10).astype(np.float32)
      yield {"image": image, "bias": bias}

[{"sha":"1aa6d2eac161e940a9c08f2827666427588e2971","author":{"name":"Jacques Pienaar","email":"8b5f536c3e2f2b8ae266b27bc9085a584b5bd904@google.com"},"message":"Document that alias renaming could lead to failures

Selective op registration uses a textual representation of the C++ type which could mismatch with renaming to underlying type if the header is pre-generated and checked in. In which case the checked in header file would need to be updated else execution would fail with missing kernels (e.g., kernels would have been filtered out as the allowlist has different spelling).

Commit b237189e6c8a4f97be59f08c63cdcb1f2f4680a8 implemented an option to
set the default seccomp profile in the daemon configuration. When that PR
was reviewed, it was discussed to have the option accept the path to a custom
profile JSON file; https://github.com/moby/moby/pull/26276#issuecomment-253546966

However, in the implementation, the special "unconfined" value was not taken into
account. The "unconfined" value is meant to disable seccomp (more factually:
run with an empty profile).

While it's likely possible to achieve this by creating a file with an an empty
(`{}`) profile, and passing the path to that file, it's inconsistent with the
`--security-opt seccomp=unconfined` option on `docker run` and `docker create`,
which is both confusing, and makes it harder to use (especially on Docker Desktop,
where there's no direct access to the VM's filesystem).

This patch adds the missing check for the special "unconfined" value.

As TFLite team delivered the Signature concept recently
(https://www.tensorflow.org/lite/guide/signatures), it is a good time to rethink
about the representative_dataset method behavior.

As per the TensorFlow product design and TensorFlow MLIR behaviors, it is
really impossible to keep the input ordering same as before.

Instead of depending on the tensor indices, it would be better to depend on the
input names, specified in the signature table.

For example,

def representative_dataset():
    for _ in range(100):
      image = np.random.rand(1, 244, 244, 3).astype(np.float32)
      bias = np.random.rand(1, 10).astype(np.float32)
      yield {"image": image, "bias": bias}

## Summary

This commit fixes an issue where DevTools would currently not correctly extract the hook names for a hook call when the hook call was nested under *another* hook call, e.g.:

```javascript
function Component() {
  const InnerComponent = useMemo(() => () => {
    const [state, setState] = useState(0);

    return state;
  }); 
  return null;
};
```

Although it seems pretty rare to encounter this case in actual product code, DevTools wasn't handling it correctly:

**Expected Names:**
- `InnerComponent` for the `useMemo()` call.
- `state` for the `useState()` call.

**Actual**
- `InnerComponent` for the `useMemo()` call.
- `InnerComponent` for the `useState()` call.

The reason that we were extracting the name for the nested hook call incorrectly is that the `checkNodeLocation` function (which attempts to check if the location of the hook matches the location in the original source code), was too "lenient" and would return a match even if the start lines of the locations didn't match.

Specifically, for our example, it would consider that the location of the outer hook call "matched" the location of the inner hook call (even though they were on different lines), and would then return the wrong hook name.


### Fix

The fix in this commit is to update the `checkNodeLocation` function to more strictly check for matching start lines. The assumption here is that if 2 locations are on different starting lines, they can't possibly correspond to the same hook call.

- Tests still pass
  - yarn test
  - yarn test-build-devtools
- new regression tests added
- named hooks still work on manual test of browser extension on a few different apps (code sandbox, create-react-app, internally).

## Summary

Adds support for statically extracting names for hook calls from source code, and extending source maps with that information so that DevTools does not have to directly parse source code at runtime, which will speed up the Named Hooks feature and allow it to be enabled by default.

Specifically, this PR includes the following parts:

- [x] Adding logic to statically extract relevant hook names from the parsed source code (i.e. the babel ast). Note that this logic differs slightly from the existing logic in that the existing logic also uses runtime information from DevTools (such as whether given hooks are a custom hook) to extract names for hooks, whereas this code is meant to run entirely at build time, so it does not rely on that information.
- [x] Generating an encoded "hook map", which encodes the information about a hooks *original* source location, and it's corresponding name. This "hook map" will be used to generate extended source maps, included tentatively under an extra `x_react_hook_map` field. The map itself is formatted and encoded in a very similar way as how the `names` and `mappings` fields of a standard source map are encoded ( = Base64 VLQ delta coding representing offsets into a string array), and how the "function map" in Metro is encoded, as suggested in #21782. Note that this initial version uses a very basic format, and we are not implementing our own custom encoding, but reusing the `encode` function from `sourcemap-codec`.
- [x] Updating the logic in `parseHookNames` to check if the source maps have been extended with the hook map information, and if so use that information to extract the hook names without loading the original source code. In this PR we are manually generating extended source maps in our tests in order to test that this functionality works as expected, even though we are not actually generating the extended source maps in production.

The second stage of this work, which will likely need to occur outside this repo, is to update bundlers such as Metro to use these new primitives to actually generate source maps that DevTools can use.

### Follow-ups

- Enable named hooks by default when extended source maps are present
- Support looking up hook names when column numbers are not present in source map.
- Measure performance improvement of using extended source maps (manual testing suggests ~4 to 5x faster)
- Update relevant bundlers to generate extended source maps.

## Test Plan

- yarn flow
- Tests still pass
  - yarn test
  - yarn test-build-devtools
- Named hooks still work on manual test of browser extension on a few different apps (code sandbox, create-react-app, facebook).
- For new functionality:
  - New tests for statically extracting hook names.
  - New tests for using extended source maps to look up hook names at runtime.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ShroXd/react/commits/88d121899aca8fec537003360010f077f0880541"},{"sha":"280e3f936f89583b44e10f29ed0ed0155b50ab8a","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTools: Scheduling profiler: Add vertical scroll bar (#22005)

## Summary

Follow up from https://github.com/facebook/react/pull/22010.

As suggested by @motiz88, update the way the react sources metadata is stored within the fb sources metadata. Specifically,  instead of `x_facebook_sources` directly containing a hook map in the second position of the metadata tuple for a given source, it contains the react sources metadata itself, which is also a tuple of react sources metadata for a given source, and which contains the hook map in the first position. This way the react sources metadata tuple can be extended to contain more react-specific metadata without taking up more positions in the top-level facebook sources metadata.

As part of this change:
- Adds more precise Flow types, mostly borrowed from Metro
- Fixes the facebook sources field name (we were using `x_fb_sources` but it should be `x_facebook_sources`

Compile a small shared library that performs an x86 CPU feature guard
check that compares the features enabled during compile-time with the
features available at run-time (using the `CPUID` instruction). This
comparison is done during static initialization and the process is
aborted with an error message if we have compiled with a feature that is
not supported by the current CPU.

Such a check is already performed during static initialization of the
library `libtensorflow_framework.so.2`, but since this library performs
many actions during initialization, there is a high risk of triggering
an illegal instruction before we reach the check, depending on the
(undefined) static initialization order.

Because of this we compile a separate shared library that we load as a
self-check before loading `_pywrap_tensorflow_internal.so`.

We also change to use `<iostream>` for printing in case of a failed
check, as use of the logging framework might itself trigger an
illegal instruction (it did in my testing).

Tested by attempting to use a wheel built with AVX-512 on an AMD CPU:

Before:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
Illegal instruction
```

After:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
The TensorFlow library was compiled to use AVX512F instructions, but these aren't available on your machine.
Aborted

[{"sha":"ed577c0d02739d7176cbaf043ac460a4404f22a8","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Escape hatch for atomic changes to both TF and TFRT.

A change that affects both TFRT and TF usually needs to be staged (land TFRT changes first without breaking TF, then update TF). Sometimes this requires prep changes to TF or cleanup changes to TFRT. Other times even that is tricky.

For these cases, one can add the TFRT changes as a patch to TF's //third_party/tf_runtime/workspace.bzl. The job which bumps TF's TFRT version will remove the patch again.

[{"sha":"b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20","author":{"name":"Håkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Add pre-load CPU feature guard check

Compile a small shared library that performs an x86 CPU feature guard
check that compares the features enabled during compile-time with the
features available at run-time (using the `CPUID` instruction). This
comparison is done during static initialization and the process is
aborted with an error message if we have compiled with a feature that is
not supported by the current CPU.

Such a check is already performed during static initialization of the
library `libtensorflow_framework.so.2`, but since this library performs
many actions during initialization, there is a high risk of triggering
an illegal instruction before we reach the check, depending on the
(undefined) static initialization order.

Because of this we compile a separate shared library that we load as a
self-check before loading `_pywrap_tensorflow_internal.so`.

We also change to use `<iostream>` for printing in case of a failed
check, as use of the logging framework might itself trigger an
illegal instruction (it did in my testing).

Tested by attempting to use a wheel built with AVX-512 on an AMD CPU:

Before:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
Illegal instruction
```

After:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
The TensorFlow library was compiled to use AVX512F instructions, but these aren't available on your machine.
Aborted

[{"sha":"88d121899aca8fec537003360010f077f0880541","author":{"name":"Juan","email":"bfe93a71cb86c31fefdccaf2f35c1c292a434187@fb.com"},"message":"[DevTools] Support extended source maps with named hooks information (#22010)

## Summary

Adds support for statically extracting names for hook calls from source code, and extending source maps with that information so that DevTools does not have to directly parse source code at runtime, which will speed up the Named Hooks feature and allow it to be enabled by default.

Specifically, this PR includes the following parts:

- [x] Adding logic to statically extract relevant hook names from the parsed source code (i.e. the babel ast). Note that this logic differs slightly from the existing logic in that the existing logic also uses runtime information from DevTools (such as whether given hooks are a custom hook) to extract names for hooks, whereas this code is meant to run entirely at build time, so it does not rely on that information.
- [x] Generating an encoded "hook map", which encodes the information about a hooks *original* source location, and it's corresponding name. This "hook map" will be used to generate extended source maps, included tentatively under an extra `x_react_hook_map` field. The map itself is formatted and encoded in a very similar way as how the `names` and `mappings` fields of a standard source map are encoded ( = Base64 VLQ delta coding representing offsets into a string array), and how the "function map" in Metro is encoded, as suggested in #21782. Note that this initial version uses a very basic format, and we are not implementing our own custom encoding, but reusing the `encode` function from `sourcemap-codec`.
- [x] Updating the logic in `parseHookNames` to check if the source maps have been extended with the hook map information, and if so use that information to extract the hook names without loading the original source code. In this PR we are manually generating extended source maps in our tests in order to test that this functionality works as expected, even though we are not actually generating the extended source maps in production.

The second stage of this work, which will likely need to occur outside this repo, is to update bundlers such as Metro to use these new primitives to actually generate source maps that DevTools can use.

### Follow-ups

- Enable named hooks by default when extended source maps are present
- Support looking up hook names when column numbers are not present in source map.
- Measure performance improvement of using extended source maps (manual testing suggests ~4 to 5x faster)
- Update relevant bundlers to generate extended source maps.

## Test Plan

- yarn flow
- Tests still pass
  - yarn test
  - yarn test-build-devtools
- Named hooks still work on manual test of browser extension on a few different apps (code sandbox, create-react-app, facebook).
- For new functionality:

## Summary

Follow up from https://github.com/facebook/react/pull/22010.

As suggested by @motiz88, update the way the react sources metadata is stored within the fb sources metadata. Specifically,  instead of `x_facebook_sources` directly containing a hook map in the second position of the metadata tuple for a given source, it contains the react sources metadata itself, which is also a tuple of react sources metadata for a given source, and which contains the hook map in the first position. This way the react sources metadata tuple can be extended to contain more react-specific metadata without taking up more positions in the top-level facebook sources metadata.

As part of this change:
- Adds more precise Flow types, mostly borrowed from Metro
- Fixes the facebook sources field name (we were using `x_fb_sources` but it should be `x_facebook_sources`

A change that affects both TFRT and TF usually needs to be staged (land TFRT changes first without breaking TF, then update TF). Sometimes this requires prep changes to TF or cleanup changes to TFRT. Other times even that is tricky.

For these cases, one can add the TFRT changes as a patch to TF's //third_party/tf_runtime/workspace.bzl. The job which bumps TF's TFRT version will remove the patch again.

As TFLite team delivered the Signature concept recently
(https://www.tensorflow.org/lite/guide/signatures), it is a good time to rethink
about the representative_dataset method behavior.

As per the TensorFlow product design and TensorFlow MLIR behaviors, it is
really impossible to keep the input ordering same as before.

Instead of depending on the tensor indices, it would be better to depend on the
input names, specified in the signature table.

For example,

def representative_dataset():
    for _ in range(100):
      image = np.random.rand(1, 244, 244, 3).astype(np.float32)
      bias = np.random.rand(1, 10).astype(np.float32)
      yield {"image": image, "bias": bias}

* Replace flushDiscreteUpdates with flushSync

flushDiscreteUpdates is almost the same as flushSync. It forces passive
effects to fire, because of an outdated heuristic, which isn't ideal but
not that important.

Besides that, the only remaining difference between flushDiscreteUpdates
and flushSync is that flushDiscreteUpdates does not warn if you call it
from inside an effect/lifecycle. This is because it might get triggered
by a nested event dispatch, like `el.focus()`.

So I added a new method, flushSyncWithWarningIfAlreadyRendering, which
is used for the public flushSync API. It includes the warning. And I
removed the warning from flushSync, so the event system can call that
one. In production, flushSyncWithWarningIfAlreadyRendering gets inlined
to flushSync, so the behavior is identical.

Another way of thinking about this PR is that I renamed flushSync to
flushSyncWithWarningIfAlreadyRendering and flushDiscreteUpdates to
flushSync (and fixed the passive effects thing). The point is to prevent
these from subtly diverging in the future.

* Invert so the one with the warning is the default one

To make Seb happy","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/abdugaffor-abdurahimov/react/commits/32eefcb3c5131f4d77a2195ff11a00a2513cf62f"},{"sha":"ed6c091fe961a3b95e956ebcefe8f152177b1fb7","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Replace unbatchedUpdates with flushSync (#21776)

There's a weird quirk leftover from the old Stack (pre-Fiber)
implementation where the initial mount of a leagcy (ReactDOM.render)
root is flushed synchronously even inside `batchedUpdates`.

The original workaround for this was an internal method called
`unbatchedUpdates`. We've since added another API that works almost the
same way, `flushSync`.

The only difference is that `unbatchedUpdates` would not cause other
pending updates to flush too, only the newly mounted root. `flushSync`
flushes all pending sync work across all roots. This was to preserve
the exact behavior of the Stack implementation.

But since it's close enough, let's just use `flushSync`. It's unlikely
anyone's app accidentally relies on this subtle difference, and the
legacy API is deprecated in 18, anyway.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/abdugaffor-abdurahimov/react/commits/ed6c091fe961a3b95e956ebcefe8f152177b1fb7"},{"sha":"9c7f29ebe75a7546e59038123d3b0c3515bec916","author":{"name":"Moti Zilberman","email":"8b603b22c9c89c36ffb170e88372622acf1aa8d8@gmail.com"},"message":"[WIP] DevTools: Support named hooks for >1 module in a bundle (#21790)

[{"sha":"a90195d29643c662baf4511b77dad7f2f5183de2","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Support multiple islands in resource alias analysis

Previously, resource alias analysis effectively only worked for one island
because island return resource values were marked as "unknown". Now, values are
propagated from within the island such that cross-island analysis works as
expected. This means that the analysis can now also be used after
`BreakUpIsland` pass has run.

As TFLite team delivered the Signature concept recently
(https://www.tensorflow.org/lite/guide/signatures), it is a good time to rethink
about the representative_dataset method behavior.

As per the TensorFlow product design and TensorFlow MLIR behaviors, it is
really impossible to keep the input ordering same as before.

Instead of depending on the tensor indices, it would be better to depend on the
input names, specified in the signature table.

For example,

def representative_dataset():
    for _ in range(100):
      image = np.random.rand(1, 244, 244, 3).astype(np.float32)
      bias = np.random.rand(1, 10).astype(np.float32)
      yield {"image": image, "bias": bias}

[{"sha":"99002d4a4336e2c5a9d6fd64e64dda5325af0827","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Fix unchecked int32 indexing in some GPU kernels

- Many op kernels use the To32Bit() function, which does not do any
  bounds checking and can cause silent corruption due to int32
  overflow.
  E.g., tf.zeros/ones/fill silently give incorrect results when the
  number of elements is >= 2**31.
- This commit adds a new helper function MaybeWith32BitIndexing() that
  checks the indexing bounds and converts tensors to 32-bit only if
  it is safe to do so (and only for GPU devices). This fixes the
  cases that were previously broken, and simplifies the ones that
  already had explicit bounds checks.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/raikonenfnu/tensorflow/commits/99002d4a4336e2c5a9d6fd64e64dda5325af0827"},{"sha":"dba2a5db51ee95efd79c96d18f72d962d7d8bfbd","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Simplify code in MaybeWith32BitIndexingImpl","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/raikonenfnu/tensorflow/commits/dba2a5db51ee95efd79c96d18f72d962d7d8bfbd"},{"sha":"2cf981016f64a4d185b31958403020f13a730698","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Add workaround for when num_bits=0 in GpuRadixSort

[{"sha":"b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20","author":{"name":"Håkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Add pre-load CPU feature guard check

Compile a small shared library that performs an x86 CPU feature guard
check that compares the features enabled during compile-time with the
features available at run-time (using the `CPUID` instruction). This
comparison is done during static initialization and the process is
aborted with an error message if we have compiled with a feature that is
not supported by the current CPU.

Such a check is already performed during static initialization of the
library `libtensorflow_framework.so.2`, but since this library performs
many actions during initialization, there is a high risk of triggering
an illegal instruction before we reach the check, depending on the
(undefined) static initialization order.

Because of this we compile a separate shared library that we load as a
self-check before loading `_pywrap_tensorflow_internal.so`.

We also change to use `<iostream>` for printing in case of a failed
check, as use of the logging framework might itself trigger an
illegal instruction (it did in my testing).

Tested by attempting to use a wheel built with AVX-512 on an AMD CPU:

Before:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
Illegal instruction
```

After:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'

- Many op kernels use the To32Bit() function, which does not do any
  bounds checking and can cause silent corruption due to int32
  overflow.
  E.g., tf.zeros/ones/fill silently give incorrect results when the
  number of elements is >= 2**31.
- This commit adds a new helper function MaybeWith32BitIndexing() that
  checks the indexing bounds and converts tensors to 32-bit only if
  it is safe to do so (and only for GPU devices). This fixes the
  cases that were previously broken, and simplifies the ones that
  already had explicit bounds checks.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MilanOdedra/tensorflow/commits/99002d4a4336e2c5a9d6fd64e64dda5325af0827"},{"sha":"dba2a5db51ee95efd79c96d18f72d962d7d8bfbd","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Simplify code in MaybeWith32BitIndexingImpl","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MilanOdedra/tensorflow/commits/dba2a5db51ee95efd79c96d18f72d962d7d8bfbd"}]

Change-Id: Id7c1fb0822645dd489b90ea62a49ee63346c99c9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/2612a5ef5652cf1ab4c4329c5d3eebb497042b3d"},{"sha":"b29c44dd920567b2ec121f5c64f2aed3f1263b7b","author":{"name":"Jaesung Chung","email":"935e11c5b050a3a02c4f0e08de55daf431709deb@google.com"},"message":"Disable lowering static tensor lists when the batch size is None by default

Converter forces to use the size one when the given batch size is None during
lowering tensor list ops. This assumption often fails and users consistently
report the bugs from internal/external users. It would be nice to disable the
problematic assumption by default and enable it safely when users aware of the
option.

All the existing clients, who are using the default size to batch one, have
enabled the
'converter._experimental_default_to_batch_one_in_tensor_list_ops = True`
explicitly. So, we can disable the option safely.

As TFLite team delivered the Signature concept recently
(https://www.tensorflow.org/lite/guide/signatures), it is a good time to rethink
about the representative_dataset method behavior.

As per the TensorFlow product design and TensorFlow MLIR behaviors, it is
really impossible to keep the input ordering same as before.

Instead of depending on the tensor indices, it would be better to depend on the
input names, specified in the signature table.

For example,

def representative_dataset():
    for _ in range(100):
      image = np.random.rand(1, 244, 244, 3).astype(np.float32)
      bias = np.random.rand(1, 10).astype(np.float32)
      yield {"image": image, "bias": bias}

Converter forces to use the size one when the given batch size is None during
lowering tensor list ops. This assumption often fails and users consistently
report the bugs from internal/external users. It would be nice to disable the
problematic assumption by default and enable it safely when users aware of the
option.

All the existing clients, who are using the default size to batch one, have
enabled the
'converter._experimental_default_to_batch_one_in_tensor_list_ops = True`
explicitly. So, we can disable the option safely.

[{"sha":"b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20","author":{"name":"Håkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Add pre-load CPU feature guard check

Compile a small shared library that performs an x86 CPU feature guard
check that compares the features enabled during compile-time with the
features available at run-time (using the `CPUID` instruction). This
comparison is done during static initialization and the process is
aborted with an error message if we have compiled with a feature that is
not supported by the current CPU.

Such a check is already performed during static initialization of the
library `libtensorflow_framework.so.2`, but since this library performs
many actions during initialization, there is a high risk of triggering
an illegal instruction before we reach the check, depending on the
(undefined) static initialization order.

Because of this we compile a separate shared library that we load as a
self-check before loading `_pywrap_tensorflow_internal.so`.

We also change to use `<iostream>` for printing in case of a failed
check, as use of the logging framework might itself trigger an
illegal instruction (it did in my testing).

Tested by attempting to use a wheel built with AVX-512 on an AMD CPU:

Before:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
Illegal instruction
```

After:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
The TensorFlow library was compiled to use AVX512F instructions, but these aren't available on your machine.
Aborted

- Many op kernels use the To32Bit() function, which does not do any
  bounds checking and can cause silent corruption due to int32
  overflow.
  E.g., tf.zeros/ones/fill silently give incorrect results when the
  number of elements is >= 2**31.
- This commit adds a new helper function MaybeWith32BitIndexing() that
  checks the indexing bounds and converts tensors to 32-bit only if
  it is safe to do so (and only for GPU devices). This fixes the
  cases that were previously broken, and simplifies the ones that

[{"sha":"b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20","author":{"name":"Håkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Add pre-load CPU feature guard check

Compile a small shared library that performs an x86 CPU feature guard
check that compares the features enabled during compile-time with the
features available at run-time (using the `CPUID` instruction). This
comparison is done during static initialization and the process is
aborted with an error message if we have compiled with a feature that is
not supported by the current CPU.

Such a check is already performed during static initialization of the
library `libtensorflow_framework.so.2`, but since this library performs
many actions during initialization, there is a high risk of triggering
an illegal instruction before we reach the check, depending on the
(undefined) static initialization order.

Because of this we compile a separate shared library that we load as a
self-check before loading `_pywrap_tensorflow_internal.so`.

We also change to use `<iostream>` for printing in case of a failed
check, as use of the logging framework might itself trigger an
illegal instruction (it did in my testing).

Tested by attempting to use a wheel built with AVX-512 on an AMD CPU:

Before:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
Illegal instruction
```

After:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
The TensorFlow library was compiled to use AVX512F instructions, but these aren't available on your machine.
Aborted

[{"sha":"b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20","author":{"name":"Håkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Add pre-load CPU feature guard check

Compile a small shared library that performs an x86 CPU feature guard
check that compares the features enabled during compile-time with the
features available at run-time (using the `CPUID` instruction). This
comparison is done during static initialization and the process is
aborted with an error message if we have compiled with a feature that is
not supported by the current CPU.

Such a check is already performed during static initialization of the
library `libtensorflow_framework.so.2`, but since this library performs
many actions during initialization, there is a high risk of triggering
an illegal instruction before we reach the check, depending on the
(undefined) static initialization order.

Because of this we compile a separate shared library that we load as a
self-check before loading `_pywrap_tensorflow_internal.so`.

We also change to use `<iostream>` for printing in case of a failed
check, as use of the logging framework might itself trigger an
illegal instruction (it did in my testing).

Tested by attempting to use a wheel built with AVX-512 on an AMD CPU:

Before:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
Illegal instruction
```

After:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
The TensorFlow library was compiled to use AVX512F instructions, but these aren't available on your machine.
Aborted
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20"},{"sha":"e3594cff84b705bf3af2312bf43fa3598244b635","author":{"name":"Håkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Run buildifier","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/e3594cff84b705bf3af2312bf43fa3598244b635"},{"sha":"99002d4a4336e2c5a9d6fd64e64dda5325af0827","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Fix unchecked int32 indexing in some GPU kernels
